3. Problem Context & Background
Business Problem:
Customer churn in the banking industry represents a critical business challenge with significant financial implications:

Acquisition Cost: Acquiring a new customer costs 5-25 times more than retaining an existing one
Revenue Loss: Churned customers represent lost lifetime value and recurring revenue
Competitive Pressure: Customers have more banking options than ever before
Digital Transformation: Banks must adapt to changing customer expectations around digital services
Project Goal:
Develop a predictive model to identify customers at high risk of churning, enabling:

Proactive retention interventions
Targeted marketing campaigns
Personalized customer service
Resource optimization for retention efforts
Impact:
A successful churn prediction model can:

Reduce customer attrition by 15-30%
Increase customer lifetime value
Improve ROI on retention campaigns
Enhance customer satisfaction through proactive engagement
4. Hypothesis
Primary Hypothesis:
Customer churn can be accurately predicted using a combination of digital engagement patterns, transaction behavior, account balance trends, satisfaction metrics, and product holdings.

Specific Sub-Hypotheses:
Digital Engagement Hypothesis:
Customers with declining digital engagement (fewer app logins, lower digital transaction ratios) are significantly more likely to churn.
Balance Decline Hypothesis:
Customers experiencing declining account balances (>10% decrease) have substantially higher churn risk.
Satisfaction Hypothesis:
Lower satisfaction scores and NPS ratings strongly correlate with increased churn probability.
Product Holdings Hypothesis:
Customers with fewer banking products (1-2 products) have higher churn rates compared to those with diversified product portfolios (4+ products).
Contact Frequency Hypothesis:
Longer gaps since last customer contact (>60 days) increase churn likelihood.
Transaction Activity Hypothesis:
Customers with low transaction activity are at higher risk of churning.
