6. Machine Learning Methods
6.1 Problem Type
Supervised Binary Classification: Predict whether a customer will churn (1) or be retained (0)

6.2 Selected Algorithms
1. Logistic Regression (Baseline)
Pros:

Fast training and prediction
Highly interpretable coefficients
Provides probability scores
Works well with linearly separable data
Cons:

Assumes linear relationships
May underperform with complex patterns
Sensitive to feature scaling
Use Case: Baseline model and coefficient interpretation

2. Random Forest Classifier
Pros:

Handles non-linear relationships
Robust to outliers and missing values
Provides feature importance
Minimal hyperparameter tuning needed
Reduces overfitting through ensemble
Cons:

Less interpretable than logistic regression
Can be slow on large datasets
May overfit with too many trees
Use Case: Strong baseline, feature selection, non-linear patterns

3. XGBoost (Primary Model)
Pros:

State-of-the-art performance on tabular data
Built-in regularization (L1/L2)
Handles missing values automatically
Excellent with imbalanced datasets (scale_pos_weight)
Fast training with parallel processing
Feature importance built-in
Cons:

Requires careful hyperparameter tuning
Can overfit if not regularized properly
Less interpretable than linear models
Use Case: Best predictive performance, production deployment

4. LightGBM
Pros:

Faster training than XGBoost
Lower memory usage
Handles large datasets efficiently
Comparable performance to XGBoost
Cons:

Can overfit on small datasets
Requires hyperparameter tuning
Use Case: Alternative to XGBoost, faster experimentation

5. Neural Network (Optional)
Pros:

Can capture highly complex patterns
Flexible architecture
Good for very large datasets
Cons:

Requires more data
Black box (less interpretable)
Prone to overfitting
Requires careful architecture design
Use Case: Comparison with tree-based models, research purposes

6.3 Handling Class Imbalance
Problem: Only 16% of customers churned (imbalanced dataset)

Solutions:

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
Generate synthetic examples of minority class
Apply only to training set
Prevents overfitting from simple duplication
Class Weights
Assign higher weight to minority class
Built-in parameter in most algorithms
class_weight='balanced' in sklearn
Threshold Tuning
Adjust classification threshold (default 0.5)
Optimize for business cost function
Trade-off between precision and recall
Stratified Sampling
Maintain class distribution in train/test split
Ensure representative evaluation
Chosen Approach: Combine SMOTE with class weights and threshold tuning

6.4 Evaluation Strategy
Primary Metric: F1-Score (balances precision and recall)

Secondary Metrics:

Recall: Prioritize catching actual churners (minimize false negatives)
Precision: Avoid wasting resources on false alarms
ROC-AUC: Overall model discrimination ability
Business Cost Function:

Cost = (FN × Cost_of_Lost_Customer) + (FP × Cost_of_Retention_Campaign)

Where:
- FN = False Negatives (missed churners)
- FP = False Positives (unnecessary retention efforts)
- Cost_of_Lost_Customer = $5,000 (estimated lifetime value)
- Cost_of_Retention_Campaign = $100 (cost of intervention)
Threshold Selection:

Optimize threshold to minimize business cost
Likely favor higher recall (catch more churners) even at cost of lower precision
